'comments': 2, 'created_at': '2019-06-26T09:47:30Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-23T19:15:13Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "As per my comment here: https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/issues/31958#issuecomment-500110641 IMO, the the actual description is misleading (if not completely wrong).
From https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-bindings-service-bus#hostjson-settings :
> Whether the trigger should **_immediately mark as complete_** (autocomplete) or **_wait for processing to call complete_**

The message won't be never ever be completed **IMMEDIATELY**, but it **_could_** be marked as completed **_if the function execution doesn't throw_** (autoComplete=true)
Probably the best place for adding this clarification is in the PeekLock behavior section? (https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-bindings-service-bus#trigger---peeklock-behavior)

When autoComplete=false, you should mention clearly that the function code **MUST** call Complete()/Defer()/Deadletter()/Whatever() otherwise the message will go back in the queue after the lock expiration.

Another thing that's not clear to me is if autoComplete=false, will the lock still be autoRenewed? Or should we call RenewLock()?

Of course, for autoComplete=false you should document how to get and use the MessageReceiver and the lockToken. There is already another issue for that: #32126


---

'https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-bindings-storage-blob-trigger?tabs=csharp#identity-based-connections

I am using `<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Azure.WebJobs.Extensions.Storage" Version="5.0.0" />`.

The page currently says:

> Property: Blob Service URI
> Environment variable template: `<CONNECTION_NAME_PREFIX>__blobServiceUri`
> Example value: `<storage_account_name>.blob.core.windows.net`

I get the error below when I use the documented value of the form `<storage_account_name>.blob.core.windows.net`. If I instead replace it by a value of the form `https://<storage_account_name>.blob.core.windows.net/`, I no longer get an error. I think the documentation is missing a `https://` in front of the value and a `/` at the end of the value.

```
[2021-11-05T14:35:24.921Z] Could not parse serviceUri from the configuration.
[2021-11-05T14:35:24.924Z] System.Private.Uri: Invalid URI: The format of the URI could not be determined.
[2021-11-05T14:35:24.936Z] Microsoft.Azure.WebJobs.Host: Error indexing method 'GenerateExcelFiles'. Microsoft.Extensions.Azure: Unable to find matching constructor while trying to create an instance of BlobServiceClient.

[2021-11-05T14:35:25.100Z] 5. serviceUri
[2021-11-05T14:35:25.103Z]

```

The page currently says:

> By default, the blob trigger uses Azure Queues internally. <CONNECTION_NAME_PREFIX>__queueServiceUri can also be specified, but the default behavior without it is to use the connection defined by "AzureWebJobsStorage". The trigger would need Storage Queue Data Contributor on whichever connection is to be used for these queues.

When I try it locally, it fails with the error message below when I don't specify `<CONNECTION_NAME_PREFIX>__queueServiceUri` in my `local.settings.json`. It seems like it does not default to `AzureWebJobsStorage` as the documentation claims. I am using `"AzureWebJobsStorage": "UseDevelopmentStorage=true",` in my `local.settings.json`.

'milestone': None, 'comments': 3, 'created_at': '2022-03-18T18:38:15Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-19T17:29:02Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "
I wasn't able to find a note / warning regarding Kudu not supported for Linux Consumption in our official documentation: 
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/consumption-plan
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/create-first-function-cli-python?tabs=azure-cli%2Cbash%2Cbrowser
https://github.com/projectkudu/kudu/wiki

Github issues were filed for that quite a while and PG mentioned we should document that. But it's still not in our official documentation. 
https://github.com/Azure/azure-functions-host/issues/3906
https://github.com/Azure/azure-functions-host/issues/4567

As a result, User wouldn't know this in the first place; It might also confuse experienced user that Kudu were supported for Linux Consumption now. I think we should at least add a note / warning in one of relevant docs to clarify this. 

Thanks, 
@yeahsicy

---

## Description

### skuStorage

The line
```
az storage account create --name $storage --location "$location" --resource-group $resourceGroup --sku $skuStorage
```
refences a `$skuStorage` variable and the `az storage account create` requires a storage type to be set. Without setting `$skuStorage` the script throws an error `argument --sku: expected one argument` when trying to create the storage account.

I believe `skuStorage=Standard_LRS` is missing from the variables declaration block at the start of the script. (It's in the other scripts.)

### tags

~~`tags="deploy-function-app-with-function-github"` is also decalred but never used. The other sample scripts use it in `az group create`.~~
See #422

I wasn't able to find a note / warning regarding Kudu not supported for Linux Consumption in our official documentation: 
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/consumption-plan
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/create-first-function-cli-python?tabs=azure-cli%2Cbash%2Cbrowser
https://github.com/projectkudu/kudu/wiki

Github issues were filed for that quite a while and PG mentioned we should document that. But it's still not in our official documentation. 
https://github.com/Azure/azure-functions-host/issues/3906
https://github.com/Azure/azure-functions-host/issues/4567

As a result, User wouldn't know this in the first place; It might also confuse experienced user that Kudu were supported for Linux Consumption now. I think we should at least add a note / warning in one of relevant docs to clarify this. 

Thanks, 
@yeahsicy

---

The short answer is that to be able to run on Linux with the Consumption plan model, we needed to basically use a different hosting and scale mechanism, which has a slightly different set of constraints. If you have other questions along this line, I suggest instead using [Microsoft Q&A](https://docs.microsoft.com/answers/topics/azure-functions.html). It is unclear how I can further diagnose the issue, as I lack access to the Azure Functions runtime. I verified that the app settings are indeed set from the scm.azurewebsites.net page.

### Reproduction Steps

Deploy a Function App with an IoT hub trigger using a user-managed MSI for authentication. When Azure Functions tries to start the function, you will find the InvalidIssuer exception in the function logs.

### Environment

* IoT hub trigger binding configured with eventhub connection via a user-assigned MSI. 
* The function app runs on a Windows Consumption Function App,
* The following App settings are set to authenticate via a user-managed MSI, in accordance with the docs on [Identity-based connections](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-bindings-event-iot-trigger?tabs=in-process%2Cfunctionsv2%2Cextensionv5&pivots=programming-language-javascript#identity-based-connections):
```
iotHubTriggerAppSettingsPrefix__fullyQualifiedNamespace = iothub-ns-iot-d-1000-17752060-5d3adbd147.servicebus.windows.net
iotHubTriggerAppSettingsPrefix__credential = managedidentity
iotHubTriggerAppSettingsPrefix__clientId = 7c4129d6-a91b-4d8f-b2b7-0c4d54734082
```
* The user-assigned MSI has been granted a role assignment on the resource group containing the IoT hub for the Azure Event Hubs Data Receiver role. 

* The function's Eventhub binding is  configured as follows (function.json; the function is written in javascript):
```json
{
  "bindings": [
    {
      "type": "eventHubTrigger",
      "name": "IoTHubMessages",
      "direction": "in",
      "connection": "iotHubTriggerAppSettingsPrefix",
      "eventHubName": "%eventHubName%",
      "cardinality": "many",
      "consumerGroup": "$Default"
    },
```

* The function is using the latest extension bundle publicly available: [Azure Functions Extensions Bundles Preview release 4.0.0](https://github.com/Azure/azure-functions-extension-bundles/releases/tag/preview-4.0.0).

* Windows Consumption plan Function app details:

This sentence made me think that I didn't have to set the setting AZURE_FUNCTIONS_ENVIRONMENT on production in order to have the value "Production", and that is not how it works:

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-app-settings#azure_functions_environment

Please make clear that when the setting is not present, the value is empty and that could be assumed to be Production.

'2022-02-02T06:33:25Z', 'updated_at': '2022-02-05T18:06:32Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '##### Version information

**dotnet version**: 6.0.101
**Azure Functions Version**: 4.0.3971

#### Repro steps

**Objective:** Make the function host use a KeyVault to store host and function keys instead of using azure-webjobs-secrets container in storage.

1. Create and publish a simple functions app.
2. Create a keyvault.
3. In App settings under Configuration for the function app set the following variables

- AzureWebJobsSecretStorageKeyVaultName ( not sure if this is still relevant but tried setting this too )

{'action': 'created', 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/pulls/comments/799107306', 'pull_request_review_id': 872434079, 'id': 799107306, 'node_id': 'PRRC_kwDOBFUV4s4voWjq', 'diff_hunk': '@@ -385,129 +524,153 @@ For a sample Azure Resource Manager template, see [Function app on Azure App Ser
 
 ### Create an App Service plan
 
-An App Service plan is defined by a "serverfarm" resource.
+An App Service plan is defined by a "serverfarm" resource. You can specify the SKU as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-    "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-    "apiVersion": "2018-02-01",
-    "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "sku": {
-        "name": "S1",
-        "tier": "Standard",
-        "size": "S1",
-        "family": "S",
-        "capacity": 1
-    }
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "Standard",
+    "name": "S1",
+    "size": "S1",
+    "family": "S",
+    "capacity": 1
+  }
 }
 ```
 
-To run your app on Linux, you must also set the `kind` to `Linux`:
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
+
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
 
 ```json
 {
-    "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-    "apiVersion": "2018-02-01",
-    "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "kind": "Linux",
-    "sku": {
-        "name": "S1",
-        "tier": "Standard",
-        "size": "S1",
-        "family": "S",
-        "capacity": 1
-    }
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "Standard",
+    "name": "S1",
+    "size": "S1",
+    "family": "S",
+    "capacity": 1
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "reserved": true
+  }
 }
 ```
 
 ### Create a function app

+The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-   "type":"Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-   "apiVersion":"2016-09-01",
-   "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-   "location":"[resourceGroup().location]",
-   "properties":{
-      "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-      "computeMode":"Dynamic"
-   },

-      "name":"Y1",

+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",

+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic"
+  }
 }
 ```
 
-> [!NOTE]

 ### Create a Premium plan
 
-A Premium plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using either `EP1`, `EP2`, or `EP3` for the `Name` property value in the `sku` [description object](/azure/templates/microsoft.web/2018-02-01/serverfarms#skudescription-object).
+A Premium plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using either `EP1`, `EP2`, or `EP3` for the `Name` property value in the `sku` as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-    "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-    "apiVersion": "2018-02-01",
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "ElasticPremium",
+    "name": "EP1",
+    "family": "EP"
+  },
+  "properties": {
     "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "properties": {
-        "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
-        "workerSize": "[parameters('workerSize')]",
-        "workerSizeId": "[parameters('workerSizeId')]",
-        "numberOfWorkers": "[parameters('numberOfWorkers')]",
-        "hostingEnvironment": "[parameters('hostingEnvironment')]",
-        "maximumElasticWorkerCount": "20"
-    },
-    "sku": {
-        "Tier": "ElasticPremium",
-        "Name": "EP1"
-    }
+    "maximumElasticWorkerCount": 20
+  },
+  "kind": "elastic"
+}
+```
+
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
+
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
+
+```json
+{
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "ElasticPremium",
+    "name": "EP1",
+    "family": "EP"
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "maximumElasticWorkerCount": 20,
+    "reserved": true
+  },
+  "kind": "elastic"
 }
 ```
+---
 
 ### Create a function app
 
-A function app on a Premium plan must have the `serverFarmId` property set to the resource ID of the plan created earlier. In addition, a Premium plan requires an extra setting in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring). This property configures the storage account where the function app code and configuration are stored.
+For function app on a Premium plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+
+A Premium plan requires another settings in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring) and [`WEBSITE_CONTENTSHARE`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentshare). This property configures the storage account where the function app code and configuration are stored.
+
+For a sample Azure Resource Manager template, see [Azure Function App Hosted on Premium Plan](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/function-app-arm-templates/tree/main/function-app-premium-plan).
+
+The settings required by a function app running in Premium plan differ between Windows and Linux.
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)

 ### Create a Premium plan
 
-A Premium plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using either `EP1`, `EP2`, or `EP3` for the `Name` property value in the `sku` [description object](/azure/templates/microsoft.web/2018-02-01/serverfarms#skudescription-object).
+A Premium plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using either `EP1`, `EP2`, or `EP3` for the `Name` property value in the `sku` as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-    "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-    "apiVersion": "2018-02-01",
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "ElasticPremium",
+    "name": "EP1",
+    "family": "EP"
+  },
+  "properties": {
     "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "properties": {
-        "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
-        "workerSize": "[parameters('workerSize')]",
-        "workerSizeId": "[parameters('workerSizeId')]",
-        "numberOfWorkers": "[parameters('numberOfWorkers')]",
-        "hostingEnvironment": "[parameters('hostingEnvironment')]",
-        "maximumElasticWorkerCount": "20"
-    },
-    "sku": {
-        "Tier": "ElasticPremium",
-        "Name": "EP1"
-    }
+    "maximumElasticWorkerCount": 20
+  },
+  "kind": "elastic"
+}
+```
+
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
+
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
+
+```json
+{
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "ElasticPremium",
+    "name": "EP1",
+    "family": "EP"
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "maximumElasticWorkerCount": 20,
+    "reserved": true
+  },
+  "kind": "elastic"
 }
 ```
+---
 
 ### Create a function app
 
-A function app on a Premium plan must have the `serverFarmId` property set to the resource ID of the plan created earlier. In addition, a Premium plan requires an extra setting in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring). This property configures the storage account where the function app code and configuration are stored.
+For function app on a Premium plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+
+A Premium plan requires another settings in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring) and [`WEBSITE_CONTENTSHARE`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentshare). {'action': 'created', 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/pulls/comments/799097915', 'pull_request_review_id': 872434079, 'id': 799097915, 'node_id': 'PRRC_kwDOBFUV4s4voUQ7', 'diff_hunk': '@@ -179,124 +179,169 @@ For a sample Azure Resource Manager template, see [Function app on Consumption p
 
 A Consumption plan doesn't need to be defined. One will automatically be created or selected on a per-region basis when you create the function app resource itself.
 
-The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. For Windows, you can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties:
+The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-   "type":"Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-   "apiVersion":"2016-09-01",
-   "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-   "location":"[resourceGroup().location]",
-   "properties":{
-      "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-      "computeMode":"Dynamic"
-   },
-   "sku":{
-      "name":"Y1",
-      "tier":"Dynamic",
-      "size":"Y1",
-      "family":"Y",
-      "capacity":0
-   }
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",
+    "tier": "Dynamic",
+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic"
+  }
 }
 ```
 
-> [!NOTE]
-> The Consumption plan cannot be explicitly defined for Linux. It will be created automatically.
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
 
-If you do explicitly define your Consumption plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
+
+```json
+{
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",
+    "tier": "Dynamic",
+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic",
+    "reserved": true
+  }
+}
+```
+---
 
 ### Create a function app
 
+If you do explicitly define your Consumption plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+
 The settings required by a function app running in Consumption plan differ between Windows and Linux.
 
-#### Windows
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
+
+On Windows, a Consumption plan requires another settings in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring) and [`WEBSITE_CONTENTSHARE`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentshare).  ### Create a Premium plan
 
-A Premium plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using either `EP1`, `EP2`, or `EP3` for the `Name` property value in the `sku` [description object](/azure/templates/microsoft.web/2018-02-01/serverfarms#skudescription-object).
+A Premium plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using either `EP1`, `EP2`, or `EP3` for the `Name` property value in the `sku` as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-    "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-    "apiVersion": "2018-02-01",
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "ElasticPremium",
+    "name": "EP1",
+    "family": "EP"
+  },
+  "properties": {
     "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "properties": {
-        "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
-        "workerSize": "[parameters('workerSize')]",
-        "workerSizeId": "[parameters('workerSizeId')]",
-        "numberOfWorkers": "[parameters('numberOfWorkers')]",
-        "hostingEnvironment": "[parameters('hostingEnvironment')]",
-        "maximumElasticWorkerCount": "20"
-    },
-    "sku": {
-        "Tier": "ElasticPremium",
-        "Name": "EP1"
-    }
+    "maximumElasticWorkerCount": 20
+  },
+  "kind": "elastic"
+}
+```
+
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
+
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
+
+```json
+{
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "ElasticPremium",
+    "name": "EP1",
+    "family": "EP"
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name": "[parameters('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "maximumElasticWorkerCount": 20,
+    "reserved": true
+  },
+  "kind": "elastic"
 }
 ```
+---
 
 ### Create a function app
 
-A function app on a Premium plan must have the `serverFarmId` property set to the resource ID of the plan created earlier. In addition, a Premium plan requires an extra setting in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring). This property configures the storage account where the function app code and configuration are stored.
+For function app on a Premium plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. {'action': 'created', 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/pulls/comments/799097451', 'pull_request_review_id': 872434079, 'id': 799097451, 'node_id': 'PRRC_kwDOBFUV4s4voUJr', 'diff_hunk': '@@ -179,124 +179,169 @@ For a sample Azure Resource Manager template, see [Function app on Consumption p
 
 A Consumption plan doesn't need to be defined. One will automatically be created or selected on a per-region basis when you create the function app resource itself.
 
-The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. For Windows, you can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties:
+The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-   "type":"Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-   "apiVersion":"2016-09-01",
-   "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-   "location":"[resourceGroup().location]",
-   "properties":{
-      "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-      "computeMode":"Dynamic"
-   },
-   "sku":{
-      "name":"Y1",
-      "tier":"Dynamic",
-      "size":"Y1",
-      "family":"Y",
-      "capacity":0
-   }
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",
+    "tier": "Dynamic",
+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic"
+  }
 }
 ```
 
-> [!NOTE]
-> The Consumption plan cannot be explicitly defined for Linux. It will be created automatically.
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
 
-If you do explicitly define your Consumption plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
+
+```json
+{
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",
+    "tier": "Dynamic",
+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic",
+    "reserved": true
+  }
+}
+```
+---
 
 ### Create a function app

 A Consumption plan doesn't need to be defined. One will automatically be created or selected on a per-region basis when you create the function app resource itself.
 
-The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. For Windows, you can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties:
+The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-   "type":"Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-   "apiVersion":"2016-09-01",
-   "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-   "location":"[resourceGroup().location]",
-   "properties":{
-      "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-      "computeMode":"Dynamic"
-   },
-   "sku":{
-      "name":"Y1",
-      "tier":"Dynamic",
-      "size":"Y1",
-      "family":"Y",
-      "capacity":0
-   }
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",
+    "tier": "Dynamic",
+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic"
+  }
 }
 ```
 
-> [!NOTE]
-> The Consumption plan cannot be explicitly defined for Linux. It will be created automatically.
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
 
-If you do explicitly define your Consumption plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
+
+```json
+{
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",
+    "tier": "Dynamic",
+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic",
+    "reserved": true
+  }
+}
+```
+---
 
 ### Create a function app
 
+If you do explicitly define your Consumption plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+
 The settings required by a function app running in Consumption plan differ between Windows and Linux.
 
-#### Windows
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
+
+On Windows, a Consumption plan requires another settings in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring) and [`WEBSITE_CONTENTSHARE`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentshare). This property configures the storage account where the function app code and configuration are stored.
 
-On Windows, a Consumption plan requires an another setting in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring). This property configures the storage account where the function app code and configuration are stored.
+For a sample Azure Resource Manager template, see [Azure Function App Hosted on Windows Consumption Plan](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/function-app-arm-templates/tree/main/function-app-windows-consumption).
 
 ```json
 {
-    "apiVersion": "2016-03-01",

-    "name": "[variables('functionAppName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "kind": "functionapp",
-    "dependsOn": [
-        "[resourceId('Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts', variables('storageAccountName'))]"
-    ],
-    "properties": {
-        "siteConfig": {
-            "appSettings": [
-                {
-                    "name": "AzureWebJobsStorage",

-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING",
-                    "value": "[concat('DefaultEndpointsProtocol=https;AccountName=', variables('storageAccountName'), ';AccountKey=', listKeys(variables('storageAccountid'),'2019-06-01').keys[0].value)]"
-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "FUNCTIONS_WORKER_RUNTIME",
-                    "value": "node"
-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "WEBSITE_NODE_DEFAULT_VERSION",
-                    "value": "~14"
-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "FUNCTIONS_EXTENSION_VERSION",
-                    "value": "~3"
-                }
-            ]
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/sites",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[parameters('functionAppName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "kind": "functionapp",
+  "dependsOn": [
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Web/serverfarms', variables('hostingPlanName'))]",
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts', variables('storageAccountName'))]",
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Insights/components', variables('applicationInsightsName'))]"
+  ],
+  "properties": {
+    "serverFarmId": "[resourceId('Microsoft.Web/serverfarms', variables('hostingPlanName'))]",
+    "siteConfig": {
+      "appSettings": [
+        {
+          "name": "APPINSIGHTS_INSTRUMENTATIONKEY",
+          "value": "[reference(resourceId('microsoft.insights/components', variables('applicationInsightsName')), '2015-05-01').InstrumentationKey]"
+        },
+        {
+          "name": "AzureWebJobsStorage",
+          "value": "[concat('DefaultEndpointsProtocol=https;AccountName=', variables('storageAccountName'), ';EndpointSuffix=', environment().suffixes.storage, ';AccountKey=',listKeys(resourceId('Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts', variables('storageAccountName')), '2019-06-01').keys[0].value)]"
+        },

+          "name": "WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING",

 ### Create an App Service plan
 
-An App Service plan is defined by a "serverfarm" resource.
+An App Service plan is defined by a "serverfarm" resource. You can specify the SKU as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-    "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-    "apiVersion": "2018-02-01",
-    "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "sku": {
-        "name": "S1",
-        "tier": "Standard",
-        "size": "S1",
-        "family": "S",
-        "capacity": 1
-    }
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "Standard",
+    "name": "S1",
+    "size": "S1",
+    "family": "S",
+    "capacity": 1
+  }
 }
 ```
 
-To run your app on Linux, you must also set the `kind` to `Linux`:
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
+
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
 
 ```json
 {
-    "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-    "apiVersion": "2018-02-01",
-    "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "kind": "Linux",
-    "sku": {
-        "name": "S1",
-        "tier": "Standard",
-        "size": "S1",
-        "family": "S",
-        "capacity": 1
-    }
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "tier": "Standard",
+    "name": "S1",
+    "size": "S1",
+    "family": "S",
+    "capacity": 1
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "reserved": true
+  }
 }
 ```
 
 ### Create a function app
 
-A function app on an App Service plan must have the `serverFarmId` property set to the resource ID of the plan created earlier.
+For function app on a Dedicated plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+
+On App Service plan, you should enable the `"alwaysOn": true` setting under site config so that your function app runs correctly. On an App Service plan, the functions runtime goes idle after a few minutes of inactivity, so only HTTP triggers will "wake up" your functions.
+
+The [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring) and [`WEBSITE_CONTENTSHARE`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentshare) settings aren't supported on Dedicated plan.
+
+For a sample Azure Resource Manager template, see [Azure Function App Hosted on Dedicated Plan](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/function-app-arm-templates/tree/main/function-app-dedicated-plan).
+
+The settings required by a function app running in Dedicated plan differ between Windows and Linux.
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-    "apiVersion": "2016-03-01",
-    "type": "Microsoft.Web/sites",
-    "name": "[variables('functionAppName')]",
-    "location": "[resourceGroup().location]",
-    "kind": "functionapp",
-    "dependsOn": [
-        "[resourceId('Microsoft.Web/serverfarms', variables('hostingPlanName'))]",
-        "[resourceId('Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts', variables('storageAccountName'))]"
-    ],
-    "properties": {
-        "serverFarmId": "[resourceId('Microsoft.Web/serverfarms', variables('hostingPlanName'))]",
-        "siteConfig": {
-            "appSettings": [
-                {
-                    "name": "AzureWebJobsStorage",
-                    "value": "[concat('DefaultEndpointsProtocol=https;AccountName=', variables('storageAccountName'), ';AccountKey=', listKeys(variables('storageAccountid'),'2019-06-01').keys[0].value)]"
-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "FUNCTIONS_WORKER_RUNTIME",
-                    "value": "node"
-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "WEBSITE_NODE_DEFAULT_VERSION",
-                    "value": "~14"
-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "FUNCTIONS_EXTENSION_VERSION",
-                    "value": "~3"
-                }
-            ]
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/sites",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[parameters('functionAppName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "kind": "functionapp",
+  "dependsOn": [
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Web/serverfarms', variables('hostingPlanName'))]",
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts', variables('storageAccountName'))]",
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Insights/components', variables('applicationInsightsName'))]"
+  ],
+  "properties": {
+    "serverFarmId": "[resourceId('Microsoft.Web/serverfarms', variables('hostingPlanName'))]",
+    "siteConfig": {
+      "alwaysOn": true,
+      "appSettings": [
+        {
+          "name": "APPINSIGHTS_INSTRUMENTATIONKEY",
+          "value": "[reference(resourceId('microsoft.insights/components', variables('applicationInsightsName')), '2015-05-01').InstrumentationKey]"
+        },
+        {
+          "name": "AzureWebJobsStorage",
+          "value": "[concat('DefaultEndpointsProtocol=https;AccountName=', variables('storageAccountName'), ';EndpointSuffix=', environment().suffixes.storage, ';AccountKey=',listKeys(resourceId('Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts', variables('storageAccountName')), '2019-06-01').keys[0].value)]"
+        },
+        {
+          "name": "FUNCTIONS_EXTENSION_VERSION",
+          "value": "~4"
+        },
+        {
+          "name": "FUNCTIONS_WORKER_RUNTIME",
+          "value": "node"
+        },
+        {
+          "name": "WEBSITE_NODE_DEFAULT_VERSION",
+          "value": "~14"
         }
+      ]
     }
+  }
 }
 ```
 
-Linux apps should also include a `linuxFxVersion` property under `siteConfig`. If you are just deploying code, the value for this is determined by your desired runtime stack in the format of ```runtime|runtimeVersion```:
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
 
-| Stack            | Example value                                         |
-|------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
-| Python           | `python\|3.7`      |
-| JavaScript       | `node\|14`          |
-| .NET             | `dotnet\|3.1` |

 A Consumption plan doesn't need to be defined. One will automatically be created or selected on a per-region basis when you create the function app resource itself.
 
-The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. For Windows, you can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties:
+The Consumption plan is a special type of "serverfarm" resource. You can specify it by using the `Dynamic` value for the `computeMode` and `sku` properties as following:
+
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
 
 ```json
 {
-   "type":"Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
-   "apiVersion":"2016-09-01",
-   "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-   "location":"[resourceGroup().location]",
-   "properties":{
-      "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
-      "computeMode":"Dynamic"
-   },
-   "sku":{
-      "name":"Y1",
-      "tier":"Dynamic",
-      "size":"Y1",
-      "family":"Y",
-      "capacity":0
-   }
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",
+    "tier": "Dynamic",
+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic"
+  }
 }
 ```
 
-> [!NOTE]
-> The Consumption plan cannot be explicitly defined for Linux. It will be created automatically.
+# [Linux](#tab/Linux)
 
-If you do explicitly define your Consumption plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+To run your app on Linux, you must also set property `"reserved": true` for the serverfarms resource:
+
+```json
+{
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/serverfarms",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "sku": {
+    "name": "Y1",
+    "tier": "Dynamic",
+    "size": "Y1",
+    "family": "Y",
+    "capacity":0
+  },
+  "properties": {
+    "name":"[variables('hostingPlanName')]",
+    "computeMode": "Dynamic",
+    "reserved": true
+  }
+}
+```
+---
 
 ### Create a function app
 
+If you do explicitly define your Consumption plan, you will need to set the `serverFarmId` property on the app so that it points to the resource ID of the plan. You should ensure that the function app has a `dependsOn` setting for the plan as well.
+
 The settings required by a function app running in Consumption plan differ between Windows and Linux.
 
-#### Windows
+# [Windows](#tab/Windows)
+
+On Windows, a Consumption plan requires another settings in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring) and [`WEBSITE_CONTENTSHARE`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentshare). This property configures the storage account where the function app code and configuration are stored.
 
-On Windows, a Consumption plan requires an another setting in the site configuration: [`WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING`](functions-app-settings.md#website_contentazurefileconnectionstring). This property configures the storage account where the function app code and configuration are stored.
+For a sample Azure Resource Manager template, see [Azure Function App Hosted on Windows Consumption Plan](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/function-app-arm-templates/tree/main/function-app-windows-consumption).

-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "FUNCTIONS_WORKER_RUNTIME",
-                    "value": "node"
-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "WEBSITE_NODE_DEFAULT_VERSION",
-                    "value": "~14"
-                },
-                {
-                    "name": "FUNCTIONS_EXTENSION_VERSION",
-                    "value": "~3"
-                }
-            ]
+  "type": "Microsoft.Web/sites",
+  "apiVersion": "2021-02-01",
+  "name": "[parameters('functionAppName')]",
+  "location": "[parameters('location')]",
+  "kind": "functionapp",
+  "dependsOn": [
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Web/serverfarms', variables('hostingPlanName'))]",
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts', variables('storageAccountName'))]",
+    "[resourceId('Microsoft.Insights/components', variables('applicationInsightsName'))]"
+  ],
+  "properties": {
+    "serverFarmId": "[resourceId('Microsoft.Web/serverfarms', variables('hostingPlanName'))]",
+    "siteConfig": {

+        },
+        {

+          "value": "[concat('DefaultEndpointsProtocol=https;AccountName=', variables('storageAccountName'), ';EndpointSuffix=', environment().suffixes.storage, ';AccountKey=',listKeys(resourceId('Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts', variables('storageAccountName')), '2019-06-01').keys[0].value)]"
+        },
+        {
+          "name": "WEBSITE_CONTENTAZUREFILECONNECTIONSTRING",

+        },
+        {

     }
+  }
 }

 A function can accept a [CancellationToken](/dotnet/api/system.threading.cancellationtoken) parameter, which enables the operating system to notify your code when the function is about to be terminated. You can use this notification to make sure the function doesn't terminate unexpectedly in a way that leaves data in an inconsistent state.
